
@startuml
' Class Diagram for Aircraft Management System

class Aircraft {
  +name: String
  +type: String
  +yearOfManufacture: Integer
  +nextInspectionDate: Date
}

class Flight {
  +flightNumber: String
  +date: Date
}

class Passenger {
  +name: String
  +passportNumber: String
}

class Ticket {
  +ticketNumber: String
  +price: Double
  +upgradeDesired: Boolean
}

class PassengerAircraft {
  +numberOfSeats: Integer
}

class SeatCategory {
  +categoryDesignation: String
  +hasEntertainment: Boolean
  +numberOfSeats: Integer
}

class Airline {
  +name: String
}

class FlightAttendant {
  +name: String
  +dateOfEmployment: Date
  +isChiefSteward: Boolean
}

class Pilot {
  +name: String
  +dateOfEmployment: Date
  +license: String
}

class Airport {
  +name: String
  +address: String
  +numberOfRunways: Integer
}

' Associations and relationships

Aircraft "1" -- "0..*" Flight : performs
Flight "1" -- "0..*" Passenger : includes
Passenger "1" -- "1" Ticket : has
Flight "1" -- "1" Ticket : has
PassengerAircraft "1" -- "1" Aircraft : is a
PassengerAircraft "1" -- "0..*" SeatCategory : has
SeatCategory "1" -- "1" Ticket : assigned to
Ticket "1" -- "1" SeatCategory : belongs to
Aircraft "1" -- "1" Airline : belongs to
Airline "1" -- "0..*" FlightAttendant : employs
Airline "1" -- "0..*" Pilot : employs
Flight "1" -- "0..*" FlightAttendant : staffs
Flight "1" -- "1" Pilot : has captain
Flight "1" -- "0..2" Pilot : has co-pilots
Aircraft "0..1" -- "1" Airport : home airport
Flight "1" -- "1" Airport : departure airport
Flight "1" -- "1" Airport : destination airport

@enduml

### Notes:
- The diagram uses UML standard notation with associations, multiplicity, and inheritance.
- `PassengerAircraft` inherits from `Aircraft`.
- Each `Flight` can have multiple `Passengers`, each of whom has a `Ticket`.
- `SeatCategory` defines seat types on a `PassengerAircraft`, and `Ticket` belongs to one such category.
- `Pilot` and `FlightAttendant` are employed by an `Airline`, and work on `Flights`.

